---
description: Validate every factual claim the app makes
alwaysApply: true
---

Every factual claim the app displays to residents must trace back to a verified data source.

Rules:
- Do not display data whose origin cannot be cited
- Do not present AI-generated summaries as official city statements
- If a data field comes from an ArcGIS query, the service file must document which endpoint and layer it comes from
- If a field is missing or null, display "Not available" rather than omitting it silently
- Log all app-facing claims in docs/app-claims.md
- Log all verification steps in docs/validation-log.md
- If a data source is unverified, do not ship features that depend on it

Do not imply functionality that has not been tested:
- Do not use the word "official" in UI copy unless the data has been confirmed live from a city endpoint
- Do not claim distances are accurate unless the calculation method is documented and tested
- Do not display a "nearby" count unless the radius is defined and the query is verified
- Do not label a module as working until its claims in app-claims.md are validated

Validation status labels:
- "Design-constrained" means the architecture intends this, but the code has not been reviewed
- "Implementation-constrained" means the code enforces this, but it has not been tested end-to-end
- "Verified" means tested live, result inspected, and claim confirmed
- Only use "Verified" when it is truly earned

When in doubt:
- show less data rather than wrong data
- label uncertain information explicitly
- never invent field values to fill empty UI cards
- prefer "Data not available" over a silent omission
